<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-248 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 463 189</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Oct 14 1991 v8 n41 p15(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T relates events leading to massive N.Y. net outage. (Sep 17,1991 service outage in Manhattan)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T analyzes the events leading up to the seven hour serviceoutage in Manhattan on Sep 1991, concluding that an unlikelyseries of mechanical failures and human errors are to blame forthe loss of power to a Digital Access and Cross-Connect System(DACS).andP;  A congressional memo was issued that discloses that ATandamp;Toperates 107 additional key switching facilities that employ thesame power supply arrangements as the Thomas Street switchingcenter in Manhattan.andP;  Many experts are concerned that ATandamp;T'spersonnel, backup schemes and procedures may not be capable ofensuring network reliability.andP;  All of ATandamp;T's communicationsequipment located on Thomas Street is powered by direct current(DC); ATandamp;T purchases alternating current power from ConsolidatedEdison Company of New York, which is converted with rectifiers.andO;ConEdison requested that ATandamp;T shut off commercial power and usegenerators to reduce power consumption.andP;  ATandamp;T's power devices forthe DACS and other equipment malfunctioned, touching-off theoutage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Accidents).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Telephone systemsFailure AnalysisTelecommunication Switching Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   How events unfolded during ATandamp;T's Sept. 17 outage in Manhattan.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>